SSE-S3 - s3 managed keys using AES-256 - Data at rest
    - Server-side encryption - used AWS managed keys
    - Uses AES-256 encryption
    - Default setting for all new S3 buckets
    - header is set to "x-amz-server-side-encryption:AES256"

SSE-KMS - AWS key management service
    - Encryption as rest
    - header is set to "x-amz-server-side-encryption:aws:kms"
    - KMS keys must be in same region as bucket.
    - There are additional charges for using AWS KMS keys

    - Bucket level key can be used and to reduce costs up to 99%
        - Using them will decrease the number of requests made to
        the AWS KMS service.
    - AWS will generate a short-lived bucket level key from AWS KMS
    - This short-lived key is stored in S3 for a period of time.
        From short-lived key data keys are created and are used for
        encryption


SSE-C - Customer provided keys
    - Encryption as rest
    - You manage your own keys
    - Key is included in every single http request made
    to the bucket.
    Headers used: 
        x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-agorithm
        x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-key
        x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-key-MD5

Client Side Encryption
    You manage your owns keys.

    Client encrypts data before sending to s3 and 
    then it is decrypted after it gets to s3.

    You leverage the amazon s3 encryption client
    to make the process easier.